							"text": "Accurate and Explainable Cataract Detection Using Eye Images Taken by Hand-held Slit-lamp Cameras",
							"articleLocation": "pdfs/CAI2024-2fo5urY39gdhGmFJimhucB/540900a083/540900a083.pdf",
							"extraLocations": [],
							"authorNames": "Daniel Kai Xiang Fung (Nanyang Technological University (NTU), Singapore), Di Wang (Joint NTU-UBC Research Centre of Excellence in Active Living for the Elderl (NTU), Singapore), Hao Wang (Joint NTU-UBC Research Centre of Excellence in Active Living for the Elderl (NTU), Singapore), Yongwei Wang (Joint NTU-UBC Research Centre of Excellence in Active Living for the Elderl (NTU), Singapore), Pengcheng Wu (Joint NTU-UBC Research Centre of Excellence in Active Living for the Elderl (NTU), Singapore), Yan Yee Hah (Khoo Teck Puat Hospital, Singapore), Chee Chew Yip (Khoo Teck Puat Hospital, Singapore), Wee Jin Heng (Tan Tock Seng Hospital, Singapore), Tock Han Lim (Tan Tock Seng Hospital, Singapore), Cyril Leung (Nanyang Technological University (NTU), Singapore), Chunyan Miao (Nanyang Technological University (NTU), Singapore; Joint NTU-UBC Research Centre of Excellence in Active Living for the Elderl (NTU), Singapore)",
							"abstract": "Cataract is a leading cause of visual impairment in the elderly. With a greying population globally, there is a pressing need to improve the accessibility of cataract screening. Hand-held Slit-lamp Cameras (HSCs) are often preferred in community eye screening due to their great portability and accessibility. However, the image quality from HSCs is generally inferior to that from conventional bulky fundus cameras. In this paper, we extend the pre-trained ResNet-18 neural network to analyze a limited number of HSC images (n=187) for cataract detection. Model accuracy is improved through augmenting training data samples and complementing the visual features with patients' vision measurements. Explainability (of focal model areas for decision making) is attained via extracting the saliency maps using the Grad-CAM method. Our model achieves a high accuracy of 0.96, on par with state-of-the-art results reported in the literature. Our approach demonstrates the potential of large-scale community-based cataract detection using HSCs and our highly accurate and explainable AI-assisted model.",
							"searchText": "2024 IEEE Conference on Artificial Intelligence (CAI) CAI 2024 Accurate and Explainable Cataract Detection Using Eye Images Taken by Hand-held Slit-lamp Cameras 1714006481909 10.1109/CAI59869.2024.00024 Daniel Kai Xiang Fung Nanyang Technological University (NTU), Singapore n/a Di Wang Joint NTU-UBC Research Centre of Excellence in Active Living for the Elderl (NTU), Singapore n/a Hao Wang Joint NTU-UBC Research Centre of Excellence in Active Living for the Elderl (NTU), Singapore n/a Yongwei Wang Joint NTU-UBC Research Centre of Excellence in Active Living for the Elderl (NTU), Singapore n/a Pengcheng Wu Joint NTU-UBC Research Centre of Excellence in Active Living for the Elderl (NTU), Singapore n/a Yan Yee Hah Khoo Teck Puat Hospital, Singapore n/a Chee Chew Yip Khoo Teck Puat Hospital, Singapore n/a Wee Jin Heng Tan Tock Seng Hospital, Singapore n/a Tock Han Lim Tan Tock Seng Hospital, Singapore n/a Cyril Leung Nanyang Technological University (NTU), Singapore n/a Chunyan Miao Nanyang Technological University (NTU), Singapore; Joint NTU-UBC Research Centre of Excellence in Active Living for the Elderl (NTU), Singapore n/a cataract detection eye images hand-held slitlamp cameras AI-assisted community health screening Cataract is a leading cause of visual impairment in the elderly. With a greying population globally, there is a pressing need to improve the accessibility of cataract screening. Hand-held Slit-lamp Cameras (HSCs) are often preferred in community eye screening due to their great portability and accessibility. However, the image quality from HSCs is generally inferior to that from conventional bulky fundus cameras. In this paper, we extend the pre-trained ResNet-18 neural network to analyze a limited number of HSC images (n=187) for cataract detection. Model accuracy is improved through augmenting training data samples and complementing the visual features with patients' vision measurements. Explainability (of focal model areas for decision making) is attained via extracting the saliency maps using the Grad-CAM method. Our model achieves a high accuracy of 0.96, on par with state-of-the-art results reported in the literature. Our approach demonstrates the potential of large-scale community-based cataract detection using HSCs and our highly accurate and explainable AI-assisted model.",
