							"eid": "hGVzODQXiy1HWMujceemN",
							"type": "authorPaper",
							"text": "Active Semi-Supervised Learning Based on Global Uncertainty Variation with Noise Resistance",
							"articleLocation": "pdfs/CAI2024-2fo5urY39gdhGmFJimhucB/540900a089/540900a089.pdf",
							"extraLocations": [],
							"authorNames": "Yufei Wen (The Hong Kong University of Science and Technology (Guangzhou), China)",
							"abstract": "Automatic and accurate fetal brain segmentation is essential for congenital disease diagnosis and treatment. However, voxel-wise manual annotation is laborious and the quality of annotation strongly depends on the annotator's professional knowledge and clinical experience. This problem contradicts the data-hungry nature of deep learning, especially for medical image segmentation. To reduce the consumption of annotation, in this paper, we propose a novel active semi-supervised algorithm for fetal brain tissue segmentation that incorporates the active learning techniques into semi-supervised methods to minimize labeling costs. Specifically, we present a new active learning selection strategy that leverages the global uncertainty variation of a sample to measure its informativeness and adaptively adjust the time to perform active learning according to the learning state of the network. Furthermore, we design a non-parameter pool attention (PA) module to refine the prediction of the model and resist noise effectively. In addition, we introduce symmetric soft cross entropy (SSCE) loss as an unsupervised loss function to further resist noise. Extensive experiments on two fetal brain tissue segmentation datasets demonstrate the effectiveness of our model, outperforming state-of-the-art approaches.",
							"searchText": "2024 IEEE Conference on Artificial Intelligence (CAI) CAI 2024 Active Semi-Supervised Learning Based on Global Uncertainty Variation with Noise Resistance 1712997102989 10.1109/CAI59869.2024.00025 Yufei Wen The Hong Kong University of Science and Technology (Guangzhou), China ywen196@connect.hkust-gz.edu.cn active learning semi-supervised learning global uncertainty noise resistance medical image segmentation Automatic and accurate fetal brain segmentation is essential for congenital disease diagnosis and treatment. However, voxel-wise manual annotation is laborious and the quality of annotation strongly depends on the annotator's professional knowledge and clinical experience. This problem contradicts the data-hungry nature of deep learning, especially for medical image segmentation. To reduce the consumption of annotation, in this paper, we propose a novel active semi-supervised algorithm for fetal brain tissue segmentation that incorporates the active learning techniques into semi-supervised methods to minimize labeling costs. Specifically, we present a new active learning selection strategy that leverages the global uncertainty variation of a sample to measure its informativeness and adaptively adjust the time to perform active learning according to the learning state of the network. Furthermore, we design a non-parameter pool attention (PA) module to refine the prediction of the model and resist noise effectively. In addition, we introduce symmetric soft cross entropy (SSCE) loss as an unsupervised loss function to further resist noise. Extensive experiments on two fetal brain tissue segmentation datasets demonstrate the effectiveness of our model, outperforming state-of-the-art approaches.",
