							"text": "ChatGPT vs Bard: Which is a Better Writer?",
							"articleLocation": "pdfs/CAI2024-2fo5urY39gdhGmFJimhucB/540900a303/540900a303.pdf",
							"extraLocations": [],
							"authorNames": "Ai Leng Ng (Singapore University of Social Sciences, Singapore), Justina Ong (Singapore University of Social Sciences, Singapore)",
							"abstract": "The emergence and subsequent widespread adoption of Artificial Intelligence (AI) Language models such as ChatGPT and Google Bard has sparked intense interest in the capabilities and applications of AI language models in education and language learning. However, not much is known about how AI language models perform linguistically. This study examined the effects of AI language models on the writing quality and linguistic features (i.e., lexical sophistication, syntactic complexity, and cohesion) of AI written output. Data was collected from both ChatGPT and Bard, which were tasked to answer a total of 120 essay prompts on topics related to Arts and Humanities, Social Sciences, and Science. The responses generated from both AI language models were analyzed for their writing quality, lexical sophistication, syntactic complexity, and cohesion. Results revealed significant effects of AI language models on writing quality, lexical sophistication, syntactic complexity, and cohesion. ChatGPT is stronger in producing higher quality text which uses more sophisticated words and complex sentences, whereas Bard is stronger in creating more cohesive texts. Results of the study are discussed in the context of AI language models' training methods, and implications for using AI in education, as well as in language teaching and learning.",
							"searchText": "2024 IEEE Conference on Artificial Intelligence (CAI) CAI 2024 ChatGPT vs Bard: Which is a Better Writer? 1713883594246 10.1109/CAI59869.2024.00066 Ai Leng Ng Singapore University of Social Sciences, Singapore Alng006@suss.edu.sg Justina Ong Singapore University of Social Sciences, Singapore JustinaOng001@suss.edu.sg AI language models writing quality lexical sophistication syntactic complexity cohesion The emergence and subsequent widespread adoption of Artificial Intelligence (AI) Language models such as ChatGPT and Google Bard has sparked intense interest in the capabilities and applications of AI language models in education and language learning. However, not much is known about how AI language models perform linguistically. This study examined the effects of AI language models on the writing quality and linguistic features (i.e., lexical sophistication, syntactic complexity, and cohesion) of AI written output. Data was collected from both ChatGPT and Bard, which were tasked to answer a total of 120 essay prompts on topics related to Arts and Humanities, Social Sciences, and Science. The responses generated from both AI language models were analyzed for their writing quality, lexical sophistication, syntactic complexity, and cohesion. Results revealed significant effects of AI language models on writing quality, lexical sophistication, syntactic complexity, and cohesion. ChatGPT is stronger in producing higher quality text which uses more sophisticated words and complex sentences, whereas Bard is stronger in creating more cohesive texts. Results of the study are discussed in the context of AI language models' training methods, and implications for using AI in education, as well as in language teaching and learning.",
