							"text": "Confidential and Protected Disease Classifier Using Fully Homomorphic Encryption",
							"articleLocation": "pdfs/CAI2024-2fo5urY39gdhGmFJimhucB/540900a355/540900a355.pdf",
							"extraLocations": [],
							"authorNames": "Aditya Malik (University at Buffalo, The State University of New York, USA), Nalini Ratha (University at Buffalo, The State University of New York, USA), Bharat Yalavarthi (University at Buffalo, The State University of New York, USA), Tilak Sharma (University at Buffalo, The State University of New York, USA), Arjun Kaushik (University at Buffalo, The State University of New York, USA), Charanjit Jutla (IBM Research, USA)",
							"abstract": "With the rapid surge in the prevalence of Large Language Models (LLMs), individuals are increasingly turning to conversational AI for initial insights across various domains, including health-related inquiries such as disease diagnosis. Many users seek potential causes on platforms like ChatGPT or Bard before consulting a medical professional for their ailment. These platforms offer valuable benefits by streamlining the diagnosis process, alleviating the significant workload of healthcare practitioners, and saving users both time and money by avoiding unnecessary doctor visits. However, Despite the convenience of such platforms, sharing personal medical data online poses risks, including the presence of malicious platforms or potential eavesdropping by attackers. To address privacy concerns, we propose a novel framework combining FHE and Deep Learning for a secure and private diagnosis system. Operating on a question-and-answer-based model akin to an interaction with a medical practitioner, this end-to-end secure system employs Fully Homomorphic Encryption (FHE) to handle encrypted input data. Given FHE's computational constraints, we adapt deep neural networks and activation functions to the encryted domain. Further, we also propose a faster algorithm to compute summation of ciphertext elements. Through rigorous experiments, we demonstrate the efficacy of our approach. The proposed framework achieves strict security and privacy with minimal loss in performance.",
							"searchText": "2024 IEEE Conference on Artificial Intelligence (CAI) CAI 2024 Confidential and Protected Disease Classifier Using Fully Homomorphic Encryption 1714096993671 10.1109/CAI59869.2024.00074 Aditya Malik University at Buffalo, The State University of New York, USA amalik28@buffalo.edu Nalini Ratha University at Buffalo, The State University of New York, USA nratha@buffalo.edu Bharat Yalavarthi University at Buffalo, The State University of New York, USA byalavar@buffalo.edu Tilak Sharma University at Buffalo, The State University of New York, USA tilaksha@buffalo.edu Arjun Kaushik University at Buffalo, The State University of New York, USA kaushik3@buffalo.edu Charanjit Jutla IBM Research, USA csjutla@us.ibm.com Disease classifier Fully Homomorphic Encryption Deep Learning Privacy With the rapid surge in the prevalence of Large Language Models (LLMs), individuals are increasingly turning to conversational AI for initial insights across various domains, including health-related inquiries such as disease diagnosis. Many users seek potential causes on platforms like ChatGPT or Bard before consulting a medical professional for their ailment. These platforms offer valuable benefits by streamlining the diagnosis process, alleviating the significant workload of healthcare practitioners, and saving users both time and money by avoiding unnecessary doctor visits. However, Despite the convenience of such platforms, sharing personal medical data online poses risks, including the presence of malicious platforms or potential eavesdropping by attackers. To address privacy concerns, we propose a novel framework combining FHE and Deep Learning for a secure and private diagnosis system. Operating on a question-and-answer-based model akin to an interaction with a medical practitioner, this end-to-end secure system employs Fully Homomorphic Encryption (FHE) to handle encrypted input data. Given FHE's computational constraints, we adapt deep neural networks and activation functions to the encryted domain. Further, we also propose a faster algorithm to compute summation of ciphertext elements. Through rigorous experiments, we demonstrate the efficacy of our approach. The proposed framework achieves strict security and privacy with minimal loss in performance.",
