							"text": "Fast-Converging Decentralized ADMM for Consensus Optimization",
							"articleLocation": "pdfs/CAI2024-2fo5urY39gdhGmFJimhucB/540900a576/540900a576.pdf",
							"extraLocations": [],
							"authorNames": "Jeannie He (KTH Royal Institute of Technology, Sweden), Ming Xiao (KTH Royal Institute of Technology, Sweden), Mikael Skoglund (KTH Royal Institute of Technology, Sweden)",
							"abstract": "For its well-established convergence properties and applicability to various optimization problems, the alternating direction method of multipliers (ADMM) has been at the center of several research fields. When applied to distributed problems such as consensus optimization, ADMM is typically implemented in a centralized manner. Such implementations are, however, discouraged for e.g. their dependency on the location and capacity of the central node. While there are decentralized alternatives, these implementations are either computationally and communication-wise expensive or slow. This is because existing decentralized alternatives require all worker nodes to either replicate the work of synchronizing the outputs from all nodes or execute their tasks in sequence. To address this problem, we propose a fast-converging decentralized ADMM (FCD-ADMM) algorithm. Through theoretical analysis, we prove the convergence properties of FCD-ADMM and show that FCD-ADMM can converge faster than its centralized alternative without sacrificing accuracy. As shown in our numerical experiments, FCD-ADMM can converge to the same or better solution faster than several state-of-the-art alternatives.",
							"searchText": "2024 IEEE Conference on Artificial Intelligence (CAI) CAI 2024 Fast-Converging Decentralized ADMM for Consensus Optimization 1713495268519 10.1109/CAI59869.2024.00114 Jeannie He KTH Royal Institute of Technology, Sweden jeannie@kth.se Ming Xiao KTH Royal Institute of Technology, Sweden mingx@kth.se Mikael Skoglund KTH Royal Institute of Technology, Sweden skoglund@kth.se Alternating Direction Method of Multipliers (ADMM) decentralized optimization distributed optimization consensus optimization convergence rate For its well-established convergence properties and applicability to various optimization problems, the alternating direction method of multipliers (ADMM) has been at the center of several research fields. When applied to distributed problems such as consensus optimization, ADMM is typically implemented in a centralized manner. Such implementations are, however, discouraged for e.g. their dependency on the location and capacity of the central node. While there are decentralized alternatives, these implementations are either computationally and communication-wise expensive or slow. This is because existing decentralized alternatives require all worker nodes to either replicate the work of synchronizing the outputs from all nodes or execute their tasks in sequence. To address this problem, we propose a fast-converging decentralized ADMM (FCD-ADMM) algorithm. Through theoretical analysis, we prove the convergence properties of FCD-ADMM and show that FCD-ADMM can converge faster than its centralized alternative without sacrificing accuracy. As shown in our numerical experiments, FCD-ADMM can converge to the same or better solution faster than several state-of-the-art alternatives.",
