							"type": "authorPaper",
							"text": "Stable Probabilistic Graphical Models for Systemic Risk Estimation",
							"articleLocation": "pdfs/CAI2024-2fo5urY39gdhGmFJimhucB/540900b333/540900b333.pdf",
							"extraLocations": [],
							"authorNames": "Taurai Muvunza (Tsinghua University), Yang Li (Tsinghua University), Ercan Engin Kuruoglu (Tsinghua University)",
							"abstract": "The interdependencies within the global financial system can cause ripple effects especially during crisis in a process called contagion. We study contagion because the transmission of shocks during a crisis can have a significant impact on society and the global economy. We apply Stable Graphical Models (SGM), a class of multivariate \u03B1-stable densities that can be represented as Bayesian networks whose edges encode linear dependencies between random variables. We are motivated by the lack of a generalized and sufficiently flexible model that can capture leptokurtic features exhibited in financial time series. Using data from 24 developed and emerging countries between 2000 and 2023, we study the process of contagion across 6 crisis and 7 tranquil periods. Our results show that the incidence of contagion is more expressed during crisis periods, demonstrating the model's ability to identify and characterize the structural relationship between random variables.",
							"searchText": "2024 IEEE Conference on Artificial Intelligence (CAI) CAI 2024 Stable Probabilistic Graphical Models for Systemic Risk Estimation 1713186460825 10.1109/CAI59869.2024.00238 Taurai Muvunza Tsinghua University gnf18@mails.tsinghua.edu.cn Yang Li Tsinghua University yangli@sz.tsinghua.edu.cn Ercan Engin Kuruoglu Tsinghua University kuruoglu@sz.tsinghua.edu.cn Contagion systemic risk finance bayesian networks stable distribution probabilistic graphical models The interdependencies within the global financial system can cause ripple effects especially during crisis in a process called contagion. We study contagion because the transmission of shocks during a crisis can have a significant impact on society and the global economy. We apply Stable Graphical Models (SGM), a class of multivariate \u03B1-stable densities that can be represented as Bayesian networks whose edges encode linear dependencies between random variables. We are motivated by the lack of a generalized and sufficiently flexible model that can capture leptokurtic features exhibited in financial time series. Using data from 24 developed and emerging countries between 2000 and 2023, we study the process of contagion across 6 crisis and 7 tranquil periods. Our results show that the incidence of contagion is more expressed during crisis periods, demonstrating the model's ability to identify and characterize the structural relationship between random variables.",
