							"extraLocations": [],
							"authorNames": "Qingshan Xu (Nanyang Technological University, Singapore), Jiao Liu (Nanyang Technological University, Singapore), Melvin Wong (Nanyang Technological University, Singapore), Ge Jin (Beijing Institute of Technology, China), Ryan Lau (Nanyang Technological University, Singapore), Yew-Soon Ong (Nanyang Technological University, Singapore; Centre for Frontier AI Research, Agency for Science, Technology and Research, Singapore), Stefan Menzel (Honda Research Institute Europe, Germany), Thiago Rios (Honda Research Institute Europe, Germany), Joo-Hwee Lim (Institute for Infocomm Research (I2R), Agency for Science, Technology and Research, Singapore), Chin Chun Ooi (Centre for Frontier AI Research, Agency for Science, Technology and Research, Singapore)",
							"abstract": "In this paper, we present the study of an end-to-end prompt-vision-physics neural network (PVPNN) to speed up the design discovery process in science and engineering. PVPNN has the potential to transform design discovery by enabling researchers and engineers to specify design requirements seamlessly via prompts, analyze available large-scale relevant historical data sets to generate novel physics-conform designs and predict the efficacy of potential design candidates rapidly. Starting from a given image or prompt for an ideal design as the baseline, our proposed framework first generates potential designs from a vision foundation model. Based on the practicality requirements provided by the user through text prompt, the PVPNN initializes a resource-efficient physics-informed neural network and jointly optimizes both geometry and physics models in an end-to-end mode. An experimental study on a simple engineering structure validates that our proposed framework can seamlessly satisfy visual preferences and practicality for fast design discovery.",
							"searchText": "2024 IEEE Conference on Artificial Intelligence (CAI) CAI 2024 Towards End-to-End Prompt-Vision-Physics Neural Network for Fast Design Discovery 1714051687352 10.1109/CAI59869.2024.00255 Qingshan Xu Nanyang Technological University, Singapore qingshan.xu@ntu.edu.sg Jiao Liu Nanyang Technological University, Singapore jiao.liu@ntu.edu.sg Melvin Wong Nanyang Technological University, Singapore wong1357@ntu.edu.sg Ge Jin Beijing Institute of Technology, China jinge52293@gmail.com Ryan Lau Nanyang Technological University, Singapore rlau014@ntu.edu.sg Yew-Soon Ong Nanyang Technological University, Singapore; Centre for Frontier AI Research, Agency for Science, Technology and Research, Singapore asysong@ntu.edu.sg Stefan Menzel Honda Research Institute Europe, Germany stefan.menzel@honda-ri.de Thiago Rios Honda Research Institute Europe, Germany thiago.rios@honda-ri.de Joo-Hwee Lim Institute for Infocomm Research (I2R), Agency for Science, Technology and Research, Singapore joohwee@i2r.a-star.edu.sg Chin Chun Ooi Centre for Frontier AI Research, Agency for Science, Technology and Research, Singapore ooicc@cfar.a-star.edu.sg AI for design discovery prompt-vision-physics neural network PVPNN design discovery computer vision engineering design In this paper, we present the study of an end-to-end prompt-vision-physics neural network (PVPNN) to speed up the design discovery process in science and engineering. PVPNN has the potential to transform design discovery by enabling researchers and engineers to specify design requirements seamlessly via prompts, analyze available large-scale relevant historical data sets to generate novel physics-conform designs and predict the efficacy of potential design candidates rapidly. Starting from a given image or prompt for an ideal design as the baseline, our proposed framework first generates potential designs from a vision foundation model. Based on the practicality requirements provided by the user through text prompt, the PVPNN initializes a resource-efficient physics-informed neural network and jointly optimizes both geometry and physics models in an end-to-end mode. An experimental study on a simple engineering structure validates that our proposed framework can seamlessly satisfy visual preferences and practicality for fast design discovery.",
