							"text": "Transforming GPP Estimation in Terrestrial Ecosystems Using Remote Sensing and Transformers",
							"articleLocation": "pdfs/CAI2024-2fo5urY39gdhGmFJimhucB/540900b453/540900b453.pdf",
							"extraLocations": [],
							"authorNames": "Yanting Zheng (Northeastern University, Canada), Ryan Rad (Northeastern University, Canada)",
							"abstract": "Gross Primary Productivity (GPP) is a critical measure of carbon uptake by terrestrial vegetation, essential for understanding the global carbon cycle and developing climate mitigation strategies. This study introduces a novel approach to estimating annua GPP in Europe and North America using a deep tabular model that integrates remote sensing data from Google Earth Engine with the FT-Transformer architecture. We utilized transfer learning to pre-train the model on extensive MOD17A2H/A3H (MOD17) data and fine-tuned it with FLUXNET station data, addressing the scarcity of in-situ measurements. Our results demonstrate that the proposed model provides more accurate GPP estimates compared to traditional MOD17 values, reflecting a closer alignment with FLUXNET observations. This enhanced accuracy highlights the model's ability to capture complex ecological and climatic interactions, offering a promising tool for advancing our understanding of terrestrial carbon dynamics. ",
							"searchText": "2024 IEEE Conference on Artificial Intelligence (CAI) CAI 2024 Transforming GPP Estimation in Terrestrial Ecosystems Using Remote Sensing and Transformers 1713911450662 10.1109/CAI59869.2024.00262 Yanting Zheng Northeastern University, Canada zheng.yant@northeastern.edu Ryan Rad Northeastern University, Canada r.rad@northeastern.edu terrestrial carbon sequestration gross primary productivity Google Earth engine transformer transfer learning Gross Primary Productivity (GPP) is a critical measure of carbon uptake by terrestrial vegetation, essential for understanding the global carbon cycle and developing climate mitigation strategies. This study introduces a novel approach to estimating annua GPP in Europe and North America using a deep tabular model that integrates remote sensing data from Google Earth Engine with the FT-Transformer architecture. We utilized transfer learning to pre-train the model on extensive MOD17A2H/A3H (MOD17) data and fine-tuned it with FLUXNET station data, addressing the scarcity of in-situ measurements. Our results demonstrate that the proposed model provides more accurate GPP estimates compared to traditional MOD17 values, reflecting a closer alignment with FLUXNET observations. This enhanced accuracy highlights the model's ability to capture complex ecological and climatic interactions, offering a promising tool for advancing our understanding of terrestrial carbon dynamics.",
