							"text": "UWM-Net: A Mixture Density Network Approach with Minimal Dataset Requirements for Underwater Image Enhancement",
							"articleLocation": "pdfs/CAI2024-2fo5urY39gdhGmFJimhucB/540900b494/540900b494.pdf",
							"extraLocations": [],
							"authorNames": "Jun Huang (Southern University of Science and Technology, China), Zongze Li (Southern University of Science and Technology, China), Ruihao Zheng (Southern University of Science and Technology, China), Zhenkun Wang (Southern University of Science and Technology, China)",
							"abstract": "The learning-based underwater image enhancement, which is suitable for batch processing, is a pivotal research direction in underwater image processing. Extensive paired image data are required in existing learning-based methods, which necessitate considerable preprocessing and hinder the application of these methods. To address these limitations, we propose a semi-supervised approach called UWM-Net: firstly, we use a compact dataset of underwater image pairs to train the Mixture Density Network (MDN) with an underwater scene setting; subsequently, U-Net can learn underwater image enhancement more efficiently. The MDN can transform standard images into underwater scenes, reducing the reliance on paired data and making much smaller training datasets. In experimental studies, UWM-Net using only 18 pairs of underwater image data achieves highly competitive results in terms of 3 metrics compared with advanced models.",
							"searchText": "2024 IEEE Conference on Artificial Intelligence (CAI) CAI 2024 UWM-Net: A Mixture Density Network Approach with Minimal Dataset Requirements for Underwater Image Enhancement 1713357355211 10.1109/CAI59869.2024.00269 Jun Huang Southern University of Science and Technology, China 12111119@mail.sustech.edu.cn Zongze Li Southern University of Science and Technology, China 12111802@mail.sustech.edu.cn Ruihao Zheng Southern University of Science and Technology, China 12132686@mail.sustech.edu.cn Zhenkun Wang Southern University of Science and Technology, China wangzhenkun90@gmail.com semi-supervised learning mixture density network reduced dataset color distortion The learning-based underwater image enhancement, which is suitable for batch processing, is a pivotal research direction in underwater image processing. Extensive paired image data are required in existing learning-based methods, which necessitate considerable preprocessing and hinder the application of these methods. To address these limitations, we propose a semi-supervised approach called UWM-Net: firstly, we use a compact dataset of underwater image pairs to train the Mixture Density Network (MDN) with an underwater scene setting; subsequently, U-Net can learn underwater image enhancement more efficiently. The MDN can transform standard images into underwater scenes, reducing the reliance on paired data and making much smaller training datasets. In experimental studies, UWM-Net using only 18 pairs of underwater image data achieves highly competitive results in terms of 3 metrics compared with advanced models.",
