							"type": "authorPaper",
							"text": "The Impact of Perceived Robotic Intelligence on Trust and Attitude",
							"articleLocation": "pdfs/CAI2024-2fo5urY39gdhGmFJimhucB/540900b539/540900b539.pdf",
							"extraLocations": [],
							"authorNames": "Amy Wong (Singapore University of Social Sciences, Singapore), Jimmy Wong (Singapore University of Social Sciences, Singapore)",
							"abstract": "Intelligent robotic agents are increasingly ubiquitous, especially in the service industry. As the deployment of intelligent agents continues to rise in frontline settings, the need to understand how users perceive these agents, form expectations of trust and attitude, become meaningful to effectively predict decision-making and enhance understanding of human-robot interactions (HRI)s. Utilizing a fieldwork approach, this study investigates the relationships between perceived intelligence, trust, and attitude. The findings show the importance of awareness and actuation in predicting both trust in robotic service agents and positive attitude toward HRI. Moreover, connectivity affects trust while dynamism impacts attitude. These findings contribute to existing knowledge regarding HRIs and offer valuable insights for firms that deploy robotic service agents in frontline settings.",
							"searchText": "2024 IEEE Conference on Artificial Intelligence (CAI) CAI 2024 The Impact of Perceived Robotic Intelligence on Trust and Attitude 1713672797368 10.1109/CAI59869.2024.00279 Amy Wong Singapore University of Social Sciences, Singapore amywongom@suss.edu.sg Jimmy Wong Singapore University of Social Sciences, Singapore jimmywongsy@suss.edu.sg Perceived-intelligence trust attitude robotic-service-agent human-robot-interactions Intelligent robotic agents are increasingly ubiquitous, especially in the service industry. As the deployment of intelligent agents continues to rise in frontline settings, the need to understand how users perceive these agents, form expectations of trust and attitude, become meaningful to effectively predict decision-making and enhance understanding of human-robot interactions (HRI)s. Utilizing a fieldwork approach, this study investigates the relationships between perceived intelligence, trust, and attitude. The findings show the importance of awareness and actuation in predicting both trust in robotic service agents and positive attitude toward HRI. Moreover, connectivity affects trust while dynamism impacts attitude. These findings contribute to existing knowledge regarding HRIs and offer valuable insights for firms that deploy robotic service agents in frontline settings.",
